          "title": "The theological center — teshuqah reversed (7:10)",
          "body": "The single most theologically weighted verse in the chapter — and arguably in the Song — is 7:10: 'I am my beloved's, and his desire is for me.' The woman has used the declaration of belonging before (2:16: 'My beloved is mine, and I am his'; 6:3: 'I am my beloved's and my beloved is mine'). But here the second clause is new: *his desire is for me*. The Hebrew noun *teshuqah* appears only three times in the entire Hebrew Bible — Genesis 3:16, 4:7, and here. In Genesis 3:16, the woman's desire for her husband is named as part of the fall's distortion of the relationship. Here, the same rare word is used for the man's desire for the woman. The reversal is not accidental. Within the world of the Song — the world where covenant love is working as God designed it — the desire that was asymmetric in the fall is becoming mutual. He desires her; she knows it and names it without shame. What the curse distorted, love in covenant is beginning to restore."
